<paragraph blockId="2.[685,1173,811,1294]" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">
JV reared 
<taxonomicName box="[805,900,864,885]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Aneflomorpha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citrana">
<emphasis box="[805,900,864,885]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">A. citrana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from girdled stems of living 
<taxonomicName authority="A. Gray" authorityName="A. Gray" box="[685,1009,890,911]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Indigofera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="740" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sphaerocarpa">
<emphasis box="[685,924,890,911]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">Indigofera sphaerocarpa</emphasis>
A. Gray
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1022,1113,890,911]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="740" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[197,228,834,853]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,816]" captionTargetId="figure-428@3.[175,1190,194,818]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Stems girdled by Cerambycidae. A) Aneflomorpha citrana in Indigofera sphaerocarpa, B) Aneflomorpha subpubescens in Gaylussacia, C) A. subpubescens in Quercus, D) A. subpubescens in Comptonia peregrina, E) Anelaphus brevidens in Ericameria linearifolia, F) A. brevidens in Calliandra eriophylla, G) Oberea deficiens Casey in Viburnum acerifolium L., H) Oberea myops Haldeman in Kalmia latifolia L." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385220" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385220/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
) from AZ: Cochise Co., Portal and girdled terminal twigs of 
<taxonomicName authority="Aiton" authorityName="Aiton" box="[877,1103,945,966]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Rhus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="2" pageNumber="740" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aromatica">
<emphasis box="[877,1035,945,966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">Rhus aromatica</emphasis>
Aiton
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="2" pageNumber="740" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Anacardiaceae</taxonomicName>
) from Cochise Co., Cochise Stronghold.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[685,1173,811,1294]" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1912" box="[709,845,999,1020]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Aneflomorpha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[709,845,999,1020]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">Aneflomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae typically feed in living terminal branches, stems, or saplings. Infested stems can often be recognized at a distance by having dying or dead leaves as the feeding larva girdles portions of the stem. The mature larva then constructs a pupal cell in the lower part of the stem and fully girdles the stem just above the pupal cell. The upper part typically breaks off, leaving a stub plugged with fibrous frass (
<figureCitation box="[958,1016,1218,1239]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[197,228,834,853]" captionTargetBox="[177,1188,196,816]" captionTargetId="figure-428@3.[175,1190,194,818]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Stems girdled by Cerambycidae. A) Aneflomorpha citrana in Indigofera sphaerocarpa, B) Aneflomorpha subpubescens in Gaylussacia, C) A. subpubescens in Quercus, D) A. subpubescens in Comptonia peregrina, E) Anelaphus brevidens in Ericameria linearifolia, F) A. brevidens in Calliandra eriophylla, G) Oberea deficiens Casey in Viburnum acerifolium L., H) Oberea myops Haldeman in Kalmia latifolia L." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385220" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385220/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="740">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). The stubs are considerably more difficult to spot because finding them requires close examination of the host plant.
</paragraph>
